<section class=3D"ch-section" id=3D"sec:4">
<h2>Cospectral graphs</h2>
In this section, we consider the question of whether it is possible to uniq=
uely determine a graph from its spectrum.  To that end, we say that two gra=
phs <mjx-container class=3D"CtxtMenu_Attached_0" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_co=
unter=3D"795" style=3D"position: relative;"><mjx-lazy data-mjx-lazy=3D"795"=
 aria-hidden=3D"true"></mjx-lazy><mjx-assistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" dis=
play=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"></math><=
/mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container> and <mjx-container class=3D"CtxtMenu_At=
tached_0" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"796" style=3D"position: relati=
ve;"><mjx-lazy data-mjx-lazy=3D"796" aria-hidden=3D"true"></mjx-lazy><mjx-a=
ssistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://w=
ww.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container> are=
 <strong>cospectral</strong> if they have the same (adjacency) eigenvalues.=
  Our first task is to show that isomorphic graphs are cospectral.  It turn=
s out, however, that there are non-isomorphic graphs with the same eigenval=
ues and we will supply some examples.  We will then use our results from Se=
ction  <a href=3D"https://tildesites.geneseo.edu/~aguilar/public/notes/Grap=
h-Theory-HTML/ch2-the-adjacency-matrix.html#sec:coeffs-roots" class=3D"cros=
s-ref">2.2</a> to identify structural properties shared by cospectral graph=
s.

